{
  "answer": "The following works in the Falsafa corpus discuss the demonic or figures of demons (typically *rakṣasas*, *piśācas*, *asuras*, or similar malevolent supernatural beings in Hindu/Buddhist contexts, such as demon armies, demon-slaying rites, or demonic pollution of rituals). These references appear amid discussions of ancestor rites (*śrāddha*), hellish torments, vows, and cosmology. No works discuss Western concepts like *daimons* (Greek \"divine spirits\"), devils, or Satan.\n\n**Āṅgirasa Smṛti** (Chapter 1): Hymns that destroy demons; *śrāddha* becoming demonic; demon-slaying mantras (*rakṣoghna*); faults created by demons.[^1]\n\n**Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana** (Chapter 1): Demon armies tormenting sinners; demon host; demon birds.[^2]\n\n**Manusmṛti** (Chapters 3–5, 11–12): \"Demonic gift\" (*paiṣuṇika-do*); \"demonic law\" for meat-eating; *rakṣasas* devouring polluted food or vows; *rakṣasas* alongside *yakṣas* and *piśācas*.[^3]\n\n**Parāśara Smṛti** (Chapters 1, 4): Demons (*rakṣasas*) eating polluted food; gifts going to demons (*rākṣasas*).[^4]\n\n**San Hyan Kamahayanikan** (Chapter 1): Protection from demons (*māra*s and the like); Copper-Faced Demon; conquering the Lord of Demons.[^5]\n\n**Slokantara** (Chapter 1): *Kiṅkara* demons of Yama tearing apart sinners.[^6]\n\n**Vīramitrodaya** (Chapter 1): Night as demonic (*āsurī*); *śrāddha* proclaimed demonic at night.[^7]\n\nNo other works in the corpus cover these topics.\n\n[^1]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-4073a6).\n\n[^2]: Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-1def2b).\n\n[^3]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 4](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/04/translation/#p-21b701).\n\n[^4]: Parāśara Smṛti, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/01/translation/#p-ed9d0e).\n\n[^5]: San Hyan Kamahayanikan, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-san-hyan-kamahayanikan-2a0c19/01/translation/#p-582279).\n\n[^6]: Slokantara, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-200f22).\n\n[^7]: Vīramitrodaya, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-viramitrodaya-d4b632/01/translation/#p-2b7f1c).",
